<div class="wrapper">

  <section class="content-section">
    <p>
      This glossary teaches how the freestyle language works: vocabulary,
      mechanics, and the compositional shorthand the community uses to name
      tricks. It is the &ldquo;how it reads&rdquo; layer &mdash; for the canonical
      catalog of named tricks, see the <a href="/freestyle/tricks">trick dictionary</a>;
      for the set-notation reference, see <a href="/freestyle/sets">/freestyle/sets</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The language is symbolic and compositional. Recurring movement structures
      compress into named operators; named operators stack onto base tricks to
      produce new ones. The same trick can usually be named at several depths
      &mdash; shortest readable form wins.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">1. ADD System &amp; Run Quality</h2>
    <p>These terms describe the difficulty of a run, not individual tricks.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Tiltless</td><td>All tricks in a run are at least 2 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Guiltless</td><td>All tricks are at least 3 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tripless</td><td>All tricks are at least 4 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fearless</td><td>All tricks are at least 5 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Beastly</td><td>All tricks are at least 6 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Godly</td><td>All tricks are at least 7 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Genuine</td><td>Guiltless excluding BOP tricks.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>BOP</td><td>Butterfly, Osis, Paradox Mirage.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">2. Core Trick Concepts</h2>

    <h3>ADD (Additional Degree of Difficulty)</h3>
    <p>A scoring system that assigns difficulty values to tricks based on their components.</p>

    <h3>Dexterity (Dex)</h3>
    <p>A motion where the foot circles around the bag.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Mirage uses one dex.</li>
      <li>Double Around the World uses two dexes.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Set</h3>
    <p>The action used to position the bag before a trick.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Uptime</strong>: before the peak.</li>
      <li><strong>Midtime (hangtime)</strong>: at the peak.</li>
      <li><strong>Downtime</strong>: after the peak.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>In modern usage, &ldquo;set&rdquo; refers to the uptime and midtime components.</p>

    <h3>Stall / Delay</h3>
    <p>Controlling the bag on a surface. Examples: toe stall, clipper stall, inside stall. Most stalls are 1 ADD.</p>

    <h3>X-Dex</h3>
    <p>A dexterity performed in a crossed-body position. The Atom Smasher, for example, uses an X-dex.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">3. How Tricks Are Built</h2>

    {{! Operator-board visual orientation lives on the freestyle landing page; the
        glossary's role here is terminology and execution detail, not visual taxonomy. }}

    <p>A trick is typically composed of:</p>
    <pre><code>set &rarr; modifiers &rarr; base &rarr; catch (stall or kick)</code></pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Base trick</strong>: the core motion (e.g. mirage, whirl).</li>
      <li><strong>Modifiers</strong>: how the trick is altered (e.g. paradox, spinning).</li>
      <li><strong>Set</strong>: how the trick begins.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Paradox Whirl = whirl (base) + paradox (modifier).</li>
      <li>Ripwalk = butterfly (base) + stepping (modifier).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The glossary explains terms; the dictionary defines exact structure.</p>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="modifier-reference">Body &amp; set modifiers — quick reference</h3>
    <p>A short reference for the most commonly cited modifiers; deeper teaching pages live under the educational pathways.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-modifier-reference">
      <dt id="term-stepping">Stepping</dt>
      <dd>A foot-relocation modifier. The kicking foot relocates mid-trick, producing a stepping effect. Stacks with most bases. Stepping + butterfly = ripwalk.</dd>
      <dt id="term-paradox">Paradox</dt>
      <dd>A hip pivot between two dexes on the same set. +1 body modifier. The set leaves and returns to the same foot while the body changes sides in between. <a href="#glossary-panel-paradox">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
      <dt id="term-spinning">Spinning</dt>
      <dd>A full-body 360° rotation carried through the dex moment. +1 body modifier. Pairs with gyro (180°) for arbitrary degrees. <a href="#glossary-panel-spinning">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
      <dt id="term-ducking">Ducking</dt>
      <dd>A head dip that lets the bag pass around the neck. +1 body modifier; one member of a four-way family (ducking / weaving / diving / zulu) defined by head direction and the side the bag falls. <a href="#glossary-panel-ducking">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
      <dt id="term-symposium">Symposium</dt>
      <dd>A no-plant leg discipline: the support leg stays off the ground during the dex. +1 body modifier. Often stacks with paradox (the "PS X" shorthand).</dd>
      <dt id="term-cross-body">Cross-body</dt>
      <dd>A general descriptor for tricks (and components) where the active foot or dex crosses the body's center line. ADD category XBD covers cross-body components.</dd>
    </dl>

    {{! Intermediate operators — compound / quantifier operators that decompose into combinations of Tier-1 primitives. Authoritative reference for equivalence-chain deep-links. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="intermediate-operators">Intermediate operators &mdash; decomposition reference</h3>
    <p>Operators that decompose into combinations of other operators and Tier-1 primitives. Each entry shows its one-line meaning, its semantic decomposition where known, and worked examples. Entries flagged <em>pending</em> are awaiting curator adjudication. See also the <a href="/freestyle/sets">set notation reference</a> for the operational forms these operators produce.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-intermediate-operators">
      {{#each content.intermediateOperators}}
      <dt id="term-{{slug}}">
        {{name}}
        {{#if curatorConfirmPending}}<span class="glossary-operator-pending-flag">pending</span>{{/if}}
      </dt>
      <dd>
        <p class="glossary-operator-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
        {{#if decomposition}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-decomposition"><span class="glossary-operator-decomposition-label">Decomposes as:</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if pendingNote}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-pending-note">{{pendingNote}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if workedExamples.length}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-examples">{{#each workedExamples}}{{#unless @first}} &middot; {{/unless}}<em>{{this}}</em>{{/each}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-lineage">{{lineageNote}}</p>
      </dd>
      {{/each}}
    </dl>

    {{! ── Symbolic compression — a worked example ──────────────────────────
        SURFACE-COMPRESSION-REALIGNMENT-1 Phase 2 / E: the three-step flow
        is now service-shaped. Each ≡ reading runs through shapeNotationDisplay
        so operator / side / core-family classification surfaces as op-token
        CSS roles. The flow is still a vertical card stack; the per-card
        readings are visually tokenized rather than rendered as plain prose. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="symbolic-compression-flow">Symbolic compression &mdash; a worked example</h3>
    <div class="glossary-compression-flow">
      {{#each content.compressionFlow}}
      {{#unless @first}}<p class="glossary-compression-arrow" aria-hidden="true">&darr;</p>{{/unless}}
      <article class="core-trick-object glossary-compression-card" id="compression-step-{{slug}}">
        <p class="core-trick-slug">#{{slug}}</p>
        {{#each readings}}
        <p class="core-trick-equivalence glossary-compression-reading"><span class="core-trick-equiv-sigil">&equiv;</span> {{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}</p>
        {{/each}}
        <p class="core-trick-add"><span class="core-trick-add-value">{{addValue}}</span></p>
      </article>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
    <p class="glossary-compression-note">
      Three names. One progression. Each card adds one operator and gives
      the result a shorter name. The community uses the shortest readable
      form &mdash; <em>mobius</em> is what players actually say, though
      <em>spinning ss miraging osis</em> is no less correct. The language
      picks its own stopping points.
    </p>

    {{! ── Execution Mechanics: concepts adapted from the PassBack glossary
        Seven micro-entries naming the mechanical details that operator
        names alone don't capture. Each entry stays under three sentences. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="execution-mechanics">Execution Mechanics</h3>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">Concepts adapted from the PassBack glossary.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-execution-mechanics">
      <dt id="term-alpine">Alpine</dt>
      <dd>Divides a trick between its uptime and downtime, inserting a duck or dive between them. Alpine Ripwalk = Stepping Ducking Butterfly. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-symposium-mech">Symposium</dt>
      <dd>A component where an active leg performs an action in a single-leg jump: the symposium leg jumps and lands on its own while the other leg remains in the air. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary, verbatim.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-symple">Symple</dt>
      <dd>Starts symposium, but mid-component the non-symple foot returns to the ground. Naturally suits some compositions (e.g., Symp Legover). The shorthand <em>symp</em> can refer to either symposium or symple, whichever the component would naturally be done as. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-muted">Muted</dt>
      <dd>An active leg held in the air for an entire component without planting. Mostly used for dexes, but applies to other components too. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-dex-window">Dex window</dt>
      <dd>The phantom space the leg draws around the bag while the dex is performed. A <em>deep</em> dex sits high in the window; a <em>thin</em> dex sits at the edge, closer to the shoe; a <em>the</em> component misses the window entirely. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-hippy-leggy">Hippy vs leggy</dt>
      <dd>Every dex is one of two motion styles. A <em>hippy</em> dex draws its motion from the hip: the thigh circles the bag. A <em>leggy</em> dex draws its motion from the knee: the calf circles the bag. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>

      <dt id="term-phases-sides">Phases and sides</dt>
      <dd>Tricks break into three phases by bag direction: <em>uptime</em> (bag rising), <em>midtime</em> (the peak), <em>downtime</em> (bag falling). A side modifier &mdash; same-side (<code>ss</code> / near) or opposite (<code>op</code> / far) &mdash; connects each component to its predecessor. <code>ss</code> is implied for clipper-led tricks; <code>op</code> for toe-led tricks. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">PassBack glossary.</span></dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">4. Naming &amp; Evolution</h2>
    <p>Freestyle naming evolves over time, and the same trick may carry multiple names.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Older Name</th><th>Modern Name</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Toe Blur</td><td>Quantum Mirage</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Toe Ripwalk</td><td>Quantum Butterfly</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Spyro</td><td>Inspin</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Abbreviations</h3>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>PS Whirl</td><td>Paradox Symposium Whirl.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PDX</td><td>Paradox.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>SS</td><td>Same Side.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Some names persist historically even when structure is identical.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">5. Runs, Combos, and Style</h2>
    <p>These describe how tricks are used, not how they are defined.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Run</strong>: a continuous sequence of tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Shuffle</strong>: alternating sides rhythmically.</li>
      <li><strong>Link / Transition</strong>: the connection between tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Connector Trick</strong>: a trick commonly used to maintain flow. Whirl-family tricks often act as connectors.</li>
      <li><strong>Dropless</strong>: a run without drops.</li>
      <li><strong>Density</strong>: average ADD per trick in a run.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Circle</strong>: a group format where players take turns performing runs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">6. Play Quality &amp; Style</h2>
    <p>These describe execution quality rather than structure.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Clean</td><td>Fully controlled, clearly executed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sloppy</td><td>Poorly controlled execution.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Thin</td><td>A dex that barely clears the bag.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Slurry</td><td>Dex completed too early; not clean.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Froggy</td><td>Body motion begins before the set completes.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>These do not affect canonical trick definitions.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">7. Trick Families</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>family</strong> is a group of tricks that share a common
      structural anchor — usually a base trick like whirl, butterfly, mirage,
      osis, or torque. The family name is the anchor; modifiers and sets
      branch off from it to create the full lineage of named compounds.
    </p>
    <p>Families matter because they tell you:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Where a trick comes from</strong> — paradox-whirl, spinning-whirl, and symposium-whirl all live in the whirl family because they're whirl with a different modifier on top.</li>
      <li><strong>What's nearby</strong> — when you learn a family's anchor, you've unlocked a path into many compounds at once. Whirl opens the door to roughly a dozen tricks; butterfly anchors another dozen.</li>
      <li><strong>How difficulty scales</strong> — within a family, ADD difficulty climbs as more modifiers stack on top of the anchor. The family becomes a difficulty ladder.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a> groups by family
      (use the family-view toggle). The trick-detail page for any compound
      shows its family ladder so you can see siblings at a glance.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="notation">
    <h2 class="section-heading">8. Symbolic Compression &mdash; how trick names encode structure</h2>
    <p class="glossary-thesis">
      The language evolves by compressing recurring compositional structures
      into shorter readable symbolic forms.
    </p>
    <p>
      The longer you stack operators on a base, the longer the name &mdash;
      until the community converges on a shorter shorthand. Jobs notation
      is that shorthand made legible. A trick called &ldquo;mobius&rdquo;
      decompresses to &ldquo;spinning ss torque&rdquo;, and further to
      &ldquo;spinning ss miraging osis&rdquo;. All three forms are legitimate;
      the community uses the shortest readable one. See the
      <a href="#symbolic-compression-flow">symbolic-compression flow in &sect;3</a>
      for a worked example.
    </p>
    <p>Notation makes that structure visible:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What goes in the <em>set</em> — the launch position the trick begins from (atomic, pixie, quantum, and so on).</li>
      <li>What <em>modifiers</em> are layered on — body-position modifiers (paradox, ducking, symposium) and rotational modifiers (spinning, blurry, gyro).</li>
      <li>What the <em>base trick</em> is — the structural anchor the move resolves to (whirl, mirage, butterfly, torque…).</li>
      <li>How the trick <em>catches</em> — toe stall, clipper stall, or one of the body-position delays.</li>
      <li>Which <em>family</em> the trick belongs to, by virtue of its base.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>A beginner example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      A trick whose notation is just <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{/each}}{{/with}}</code>
      is itself the family anchor. It carries one body rotation and resolves
      at its catch — no modifiers stacked on, no set primitive prefacing it.
      A single token tells you: this is the structural root.
    </p>

    <h3>A compound example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.paradoxWhirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      A whirl with the paradox modifier applied. The notation reads
      left-to-right exactly as the trick is built: the modifier (yellow-olive)
      shapes the body position; the base anchor (green) provides the rotation
      and family identity. Adds 1 ADD on top of whirl's base difficulty.
    </p>

    <h3>A modifier-heavy example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.gauntlet}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      Three body modifiers stacked on a torque base &mdash; known to the
      community as Gauntlet, a 7-ADD trick. Reading the notation
      left-to-right reveals the layered construction: each modifier
      contributes its own +1 to the total difficulty.
    </p>

    <h3 id="notation-roles">Color-coded structural roles</h3>
    <p>
      The visual hierarchy is restrained &mdash; only the four primary roles
      (core family, set, rotation, body modifier) carry color saturation.
      Hover any token on a trick page to see its role and resolved family name.
    </p>

    <p class="glossary-section-bridge">
      The next section describes the operational layer &mdash; how the trick
      is executed. Symbolic compression lives in trick names; operational
      mechanics live in the sequence of plants, dexes, and contacts.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="operational-notation">
    <h2 class="section-heading">9. Operational Notation</h2>

    {{! ── Hard layer separation: semantic vs operational notation ──────── }}
    <table class="glossary-layer-contrast">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Describes</th><th>Renders as</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Semantic</strong> (&sect;8)</td>
          <td>Compositional structure &mdash; what the trick <em>is</em></td>
          <td>Operator stack (e.g., <code>stepping ducking paradox torque</code>)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Operational</strong> (&sect;9)</td>
          <td>Execution mechanics &mdash; what the body <em>does</em></td>
          <td>Bracket-flagged sequence (e.g., <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX] &gt; OP OUT [DEX] &gt; [DEL] CLIP</code>)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      The two layers are complementary, not interchangeable. The same trick
      may be named at several semantic stopping depths yet still have a
      single canonical operational form. Trick-detail pages render both
      side-by-side when both are authored.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Operational notation lives behind the &ldquo;Set notation
      (operational)&rdquo; section on per-trick pages. This section is
      the token reference for that surface.
    </p>

    <h3>Component flags</h3>
    <p>Square-bracket annotations on a move that mark which structural component is in play. Multiple flags may stack on a single move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-flag-dex"><code>[DEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Dexterity component — the move involves bag-foot interaction (the foot circles around or contacts the bag).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-del"><code>[DEL]</code></dt>
      <dd>Delay component — the move ends in a stall on a foot or surface. Typically the final segment of an operational notation string.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-bod"><code>[BOD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Body-position component — the move includes a body pose change (spin, duck, dive, paradox).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xbd"><code>[XBD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Cross-body component — the delay or move sits on the opposite-side surface from the plant foot. Typically appears with <code>[DEL]</code> on the landing.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-pdx"><code>[PDX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Paradox component &mdash; flags a cross-body far dex requiring a hip-pivot repositioning to bring the leg under the bag. Operationally: <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX]</code> (clipper set, far in-out dex). Equivalent to the <code>paradox</code> body modifier in semantic notation. <span class="glossary-source-attrib">Adapted from PassBack glossary &sect; &ldquo;Paradox&rdquo;.</span></dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xdex"><code>[XDEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>X-Dex component — a full-circle dex variant. In IFPA's ontology, X-Dex fires only in specific named tricks (per Red pt1); FootbagMoves uses the flag more broadly.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3>Sides</h3>
    <p>The side prefix on a move tells you which leg performs it relative to the plant foot.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-side-same"><code>SAME</code></dt>
      <dd>Same side as the plant foot. Roughly equivalent to the <code>SS</code> abbreviation seen in some trick names.</dd>
      <dt id="op-side-op"><code>OP</code></dt>
      <dd>Opposite side from the plant foot. The non-plant leg performs the move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3>Directions</h3>
    <p>The arc-direction tokens describe the bag's path during the dex.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-direction-in"><code>IN</code></dt>
      <dd>Inward arc — the bag travels toward the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-out"><code>OUT</code></dt>
      <dd>Outward arc — the bag travels away from the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-front"><code>FRONT</code> / <code>BACK</code></dt>
      <dd>
        Forward / backward direction. Standalone <code>FRONT</code> or
        <code>BACK</code> describes the arc; when followed by
        <code>WHIRL</code> or <code>SWIRL</code>, the two tokens fuse
        into a single rotational-variant move (e.g.
        <code>FRONT WHIRL</code>, <code>BACK SWIRL</code>).
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 id="op-sequence-operators">Sequence operators</h3>
    <p>The arrow tokens segment the operational notation into discrete sub-actions.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-seq-minor"><code>&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Sub-step boundary — continuous flow within a beat group. The next move follows directly from the previous one without major pause or replant.</dd>
      <dt id="op-seq-major"><code>&gt;&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Major step boundary — often signals a no-plant break, a beat change, or a body-action transition. Visually heavier than <code>&gt;</code>; typically pairs with <code>(no plant while)</code> on a following move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 id="op-pre-states">Pre-move state flags</h3>
    <p>Lowercase parenthesized annotations that describe the body state during the next move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-prestate-back"><code>(back)</code> / <code>(front)</code></dt>
      <dd>Backward / forward direction of the next body action. Most often seen with <code>SPIN</code>: <code>(back) SPIN [BOD]</code> = backward body spin.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-no-plant"><code>(no plant while)</code></dt>
      <dd>The support leg does not plant during this segment. Common in dense compounds where the body is mid-air during the move.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-rooted"><code>(rooted)</code></dt>
      <dd>Held / rooted position; no plant. Corresponds to the <code>rooted</code> set primitive in IFPA's modifier table.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 id="op-surfaces">Surfaces &amp; body actions (reference)</h3>
    <p>The remaining vocabulary is small enough to list verbatim:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>CLIP</code>, <code>TOE</code> &mdash; plant or landing surfaces</li>
      <li><code>SPIN</code>, <code>DUCK</code>, <code>DIVE</code> &mdash; body actions</li>
      <li><code>FRONT WHIRL</code> / <code>BACK WHIRL</code> / <code>FRONT SWIRL</code> / <code>BACK SWIRL</code> &mdash; rotational dex variants on a rotational base</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="detail-muted">
      For the broader set notation reference (set primitives like Pixie,
      Fairy, Atomic, Quantum and how they decompose), see
      <a href="/freestyle/sets">Set notation reference</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">10. Foundational Tricks</h2>
    <p>
      The irreducible base tricks most other named tricks descend from. Each
      is a family anchor; most named compounds resolve to one of these once
      their modifiers and sets are stripped away.
    </p>
    {{! SURFACE-COMPRESSION-REALIGNMENT-1 Phase 2 / G: registry-style grid
        replacing the previous flat <ul>. Same partial as the landing's
        Core Tricks section — one symbolic-object pattern across the two
        surfaces. `idPrefix="term-"` preserves the cross-page #term-{slug}
        deep-link contract used by glossaryAnchors.ts. }}
    {{> core-tricks-grid tricks=content.coreTricks idPrefix="term-"}}

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="set-modifiers-tier-1">Set modifiers (not core tricks)</h3>
    <p>
      Set modifiers are structural treatments applied <em>to</em> a base
      trick, not bases themselves. See the
      <a href="/freestyle/sets">set notation reference</a> for the full
      vocabulary.
    </p>
    {{! Phase 2 / H: set-modifier registry grid. Entries projected from the
        Tier-1 set operator board + OPERATOR_REFERENCE_ENTRIES (set /
        compound-set categories). Each tile carries name, optional glyph,
        one-line meaning, optional decomposition, optional cross-link. }}
    <div class="glossary-set-modifiers-grid">
      {{#each content.setModifiers}}
      <article class="set-modifier-card" id="term-{{slug}}">
        <p class="set-modifier-head">
          <span class="set-modifier-name">{{name}}</span>
          {{#if glyph}}<span class="set-modifier-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>{{/if}}
        </p>
        <p class="set-modifier-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
        {{#if decomposition}}
        <p class="set-modifier-decomposition"><span class="set-modifier-decomp-sigil">&equiv;</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if href}}
        <a class="set-modifier-deeplink" href="{{href}}" aria-label="Notation reference">&rarr;</a>
        {{/if}}
      </article>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">11. Competitive &amp; Format Terms</h2>
    <p>These describe event formats and play contexts.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Freestyle Routine</strong>: a choreographed performance to music.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Contest (Shred:30)</strong>: a technical scoring format.</li>
      <li><strong>Big Trick / Sick, Big, Best</strong>: single or combo highlight formats.</li>
      <li><strong>Circle Contest</strong>: a turn-based elimination format.</li>
      <li><strong>Most Rippin&rsquo; Run</strong>: a last-player-standing format.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">12. Sources</h2>
    <p>
      Definitions on this page draw on long-standing freestyle community
      usage, expert-reviewed terminology established across decades of play
      and contests, and historical reference materials (footbag.org and
      community documentation). They've been rewritten for clarity and
      consistency. Authoritative trick-level definitions — ADD values,
      structural decomposition, modifier relationships — live in the
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{#if content.connectivePanels.length}}
  <section class="content-section glossary-connective-section" id="connective-panels">
